def: Room to extend the elbows on each side; ample room for motionor action; free scope. "My soul hath elbowroom." Shak.Then came a stretch of grass and a little more elbowroom. W. G.Norris.
A little moon or satellite. [Obs.] Bp. Hall.
The planking from the waterways up to the port sills. Totten.
An instrument which consists of links and is used in measuringland.
A chamber or a cottage. [Obs.] Chaucer.
Bearing a club or a key.

Not willing to yield or compIy with what is required or isreasonable; perverse; disobedient; peevish; as, a froward child.A froward man soweth strife. Prov. xvi. 28.A froward retention of custom is as turbulent a thing as innovation.Bacon.
A pullet from which the ovaries have been removed to producefattening; hence, a fat pullet.
To turn upside down; to subvert; to upset. [Obs.] Wyclif.
